Date: Wed 25 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: International Herald Tribune, 24 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.iht.com/articles/2005/05/23/news/china.php>

Cattle disease may have prompted return
---------------------------------------------------------
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs declined to offer any immediate
explanation on Monday [23 May 2005] for Deputy Prime Minister Wu
Yi's unexpected return from Tokyo, but the official's sudden
departure from Japan may be related to an outbreak of foot-and-
mouth disease [FMD] at dairy farms within 2 hours' drive of the
Chinese capital.
Observers in Beijing could see no other compelling reason for Wu
Yi's surprise decision to fly back to the mainland just before a
scheduled meeting with Japan's prime minister, Junichiro Koizumi.
Wu Yi, whose duties include health issues as well as trade, may
have been called back to deal with the fallout from the spread of the
highly infectious disease. She was instrumental several years ago in
removing the mayor of Beijing and the health minister for their
culpability in hiding the outbreak of SARS.
The lack of information about the outbreak near the capital raised
questions on whether officials had again been hiding information.
10 days ago, a Chinese agricultural official confirmed to an
international animal health organization that FMD had broken out in
Jiangsu and Shandong Provinces. But there was no similar
confirmation of an outbreak near Beijing, although villagers
confirmed the outbreak to a visiting reporter on Monday [23 May
2005] afternoon.
"We did have FMD around here, but it's already been dealt with,"
said Li Suanji, a farmer who runs a store that sells fertilizer and seed
to local farmers in the village of Houluzhuang, just beyond the Great
Wall north of Beijing. Over the past 2 days, Li said, more than 2000
cattle have been destroyed in villages in Yanqing County. He said
there were no cattle left now and that farmers had been offered
compensation by agricultural officials of 3000-6000 yuan, or USD
360-720.
Another farmer working north of the capital, Zheng Chao, said
"We've been isolated for 20 days, and this is the 1st day we've
been allowed out."
[Byline: Chris Buckley]
